entry.title: [user bypass] Check if the site has high site engagement index
entry.content:
Return a high confidence level for sites with high site engagement index. Having a high site engagement index doesn't mean that a site is

more likely to be broken but it serves as a signal that user has strong relationship with the site. It is useful when determining when the

entry.title: [DBSC] Check if the /RotateBoundCookies sets the required cookies
entry.content:
The cookie header is not present in the response of the cookie rotation

request that is propagated from the network to the browser process.



Unexpected server response i.e. not setting the required cookies is

considered a persistent error.



This CL adds a cookie observer to the rotation request. The observer is

called with `network::mojom::CookieAccessDetails::Type::kChange` with

cookies set in the response of the request if there are any. The cookies

are verified to contain the required cookie.



Normally, a cookie update notification should be sent before the request

is complete. We add some leeway using a timer in the case mojo messages

are delivered out of order.

entry.title: [PWAs-in-Play] Allow migration between multiple APK PWA packages
entry.content:
If multiple ARC packages attempt to install the same web app, they will

silently conflict and repeatedly switch which package is associated with

the app in prefs. Additionally, uninstalling the web app will take

multiple attempts to remove the app, as the duplicate PWA package will

reinstall it immediately after the app is uninstalled the first time.



For the case of apps which are migrating between Play Store listings, it

is possible that users who install both listings will end up in this

state, with both apps installed. To resolve this, we silently migrate

the user state, uninstalling the 'deprecated' package, and associating

the app with the 'canonical' package. We do not attempt to automatically

detect duplicates, but rather rely on a hardcoded list of impacted

packages.

entry.content:
Context:

Previously Navigation reducer use VolumeManager's volumeInfoList to

check if a volume is allowed or not, but the addVolume action is

dispatched before the VolumeInfo is added to the VolumeInfoList, which

makes the navigation reducer skip that volume because it's not inside

the VolumeInfoList. The result is that the newly mounted volume won't show in the directory tree.



This CL exposes the isAllowedVolume() method from the VolumeManager so

Navigation reducer can use it to check if a volume is allowed or not.



Note: "directoryTreeExpandFolderOnDelayExpansionVolume" browser test

breaks with the store version directory tree without this fix.

entry.title: Introduce a new BrowsingDataModel for Shared Dictionary
entry.content:
This CL introduces a new type of BrowsingDataModel for Shared

Dictionary. This allows the disk usage shown in

chrome://settings/content/all to include the disk usage for shared

dictionaries. Additionally, when the user clicks the garbage icon in

chrome://settings/content/all, Chromium will now delete the stored

shared dictionaries for the host.



Shared Dictionaries are managed in the network service.

BrowsingDataModel calls GetSharedDictionaryUsageInfo() IPC to get the

usage and ClearSharedDictionaryCacheForIsolationKey() IPC to delete the

dictionaries.



This CL also implements the OnSharedDictionaryAccessed() method in the

WebContentsHandler class in page_specific_content_settings.cc to receive

shared dictionary usage notifications from the network service. It then

calls PageSpecificContentSettings::BrowsingDataAccessed() so that users

can see the usage in the PageSpecificSiteDataDialog

(crbug.com/1413922#c59).

entry.title: Add MediaSessionClient API and ChromeMediaSessionClient implementation
entry.content:
This CL introduces a new MediaSessionClient API that will allow

embedders to determine whether media information should be hidden from

OS’ media controls. This new API is similar to the PermissionsClient

API, in which an embedder registers their own instance.



Additionally, this API will be used for embedders to set their own media

metadata placeholders (Album, Artist, Thumbnail, Title) for display

when the media information is hidden.



This CL also introduces a Chrome specific implementation of this API

(ChromeMediaSessionClient) which sets to hide media metadata if the

media is playing in an Incognito session.



As the Chrome implementation requires an icon not present in //chrome it

has been copied over from

ui/webui/resources/cr_components/omnibox/icons/incognito.svg and

converted into chrome/app/vector_icons/incognito_white_circle.icon.



This CL will be followed by a CL that will make use of this new API inside //content (https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4651207).



For more details, see DD: go/incognito-media-controller-desktop-dd

entry.title: Tweak GetOutermostWebContents usage in PrintIfAllowedByPolicy
entry.content:
The fix in crrev.com/c/4651379 works for LCAC as all URLs are sent for

scanning, but that might not be the case when cloud scanning uses this

code. When that happens, the WebContents used by

ContentAnalysisDelegate::IsEnabled also need to be the outermost one,

otherwise the URL comparison to check if a scan should happen might be

against the PDF reader's URL (aka chrome-extension://), or

any other embedded page.



This is fixed by simply moving the GetOutermostWebContents earlier in

PrintIfAllowedByPolicy instead of later in ScanAndPrint.
